  "doc_id": "51321",
  "text": "This now leads us to a potential problem with the ordered logit/probit model. When σ is the same for all cases-residuals are homoskedastic-the ratio between the β's and the α's is also the same for all cases. However, when σ differs across casesthere is heteroskedasticity-the ratio also differs [CITATION_1] . As Hoetker (2004, 17) notes, \". . . in the presence of even fairly small differences in residual variation, naïve comparisons of coefficients [across groups] can indicate differences where none exist, hide differences that do exist, and even show differences in the opposite direction of what actually exists.\"",
